records.nl_statement: Let $V$ be a vector space over an infinite field $F$. Show that $V$ cannot be the set-theoretic union of a finite number of proper subspaces of $V$.
records.lean_header:
import Mathlib

open Fintype Set Real Ideal Polynomial
open scoped BigOperators
records.ground_truth:
theorem exercise_5_2_20 {F V ι: Type*} [Infinite F] [Field F]
  [AddCommGroup V] [Module F V] [Finite ι] {u : ι → Submodule F V}
  (hu : ∀ i : ι, u i ≠ ⊤) :
  (⋃ i : ι, (u i : Set V)) ≠ ⊤ :=
records.baseline_candidate:
theorem autoformalized_theorem_1120 {F V : Type*} [Infinite F] [Field F]
  [AddCommGroup V] [Module F V] {ι : Type*} [Fintype ι] :
  ⋃ i : ι, (Submodule.map (λ x => x) (i : Submodule F V)) ≠ ⊤ := by sorry
records.best_cycle_candidate:
theorem autoformalized_theorem_1120 {F V : Type*} [Infinite F] [Field F]
  [AddCommGroup V] [Module F V] :
  ¬ ∃ x : ℕ, ∃ U : Fin x → Set V,
    ∃ U' : Fin x → Set V,
      (∀ i, isProper (U i)) ∧
      (∀ i, U i ⊆ U' i) ∧
      (∀ i j, i ≠ j → Disjoint (U i) (U j)) ∧
      (∀ i, U i ≠ ⊤) ∧
      V = ⋃ i, U' i := by sorry

records.nl_statement: A map $f: X \rightarrow Y$ is said to be an open map if for every open set $U$ of $X$, the set $f(U)$ is open in $Y$. Show that $\pi_{1}: X \times Y \rightarrow X$ and $\pi_{2}: X \times Y \rightarrow Y$ are open maps.

import Mathlib

open Filter Set TopologicalSpace
open scoped Topology

  (π₁ : X × Y → X)
  (π₂ : X × Y → Y)
  (h₁ : π₁ = Prod.fst)
  (h₂ : π₂ = Prod.snd) :

records.nl_statement: Give an example of a nonempty subset $U$ of $\mathbf{R}^2$ such that $U$ is closed under addition and under taking additive inverses (meaning $-u \in U$ whenever $u \in U$), but $U$ is not a subspace of $\mathbf{R}^2$.

import Mathlib
